        "text": "### Chemistry Insights\n\nThe Ag⁺–NH₃ system is a textbook example of linear diamine coordination. The cumulative log β₂ ≈ 7.2–8.2 (depending on ionic medium) reflects the well-known stability of the **[Ag(NH₃)₂]⁺** complex, which is the basis for **Tollens' reagent** used in aldehyde detection and silver-mirror reactions. The spread in reported values across the ionic strength range 0–5 M highlights the significant effect of the supporting electrolyte (e.g., NH₄NO₃, NaClO₄, KNO₃) on apparent stability — a reminder that \"the\" stability constant is always medium-dependent. The negative ΔH and ΔS values confirm the reaction is **enthalpically driven** with an entropic penalty from ordering solvent and ligand molecules around the metal centre.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
